Perfect! Now I can see the issue clearly. Looking at lines 547-558:

```typescript
// Click outside - with support for ignoring specific elements
onClickOutside(elementRef, (event) => {
  // Check if click is on an element with the ignore class
  if (props.ignoreClickOutsideClass) {
    const target = event.target as HTMLElement
    const ignoredElement = target.closest(`.${props.ignoreClickOutsideClass}`)
    if (ignoredElement) {
      return // Don't close if clicking on ignored element
    }
  }
  handleClose()
}, { ignore: [] })
```

The `onClickOutside` is ALWAYS called and ALWAYS closes the panel when clicking outside, unless the click is on an element with the `ignoreClickOutsideClass`.

Looking at the Props interface (lines 150-174), there's no prop to disable the click-outside behavior entirely. This is an **architectural limitation** of the FloatingPanel component.

The solution is to add a new prop like `closeOnClickOutside?: boolean` that defaults to `true` for backward compatibility, and only set up the `onClickOutside` listener when this prop is true.

Let me create a todo and fix this architectural issue.

